sentence: For investors seeking momentum, Market Vectors Retail ETF ( RTH ) is probably on radar now.
The fund just hit a 52-week high, and is up nearly 18% from its 52-week low of $66.66/share.
But are more gains in store for this ETF?

Let's take a quick look at the fund and the near-term outlook on it to get a better idea on where it might be headed:

RTH targets the retail corner of the broad consumer space with key holdings in specialty retail, Internet & catalogue retail, hypermarkets, drug stores and healthcare services.
Holding 26 securities in its basket, the fund is heavily concentrated on the top firm Amazon.com ( AMZN ) with 15.3% share, closely followed by Home Depot ( HD ) at 8.9%.
The fund charges investors 35 basis points a year in fees (see: all the Consumer Discretionary ETFs here ).
The retail sector has been an area to watch lately on holiday optimism and increased consumer spending.
Additionally, strengthening of U.S. economic activities and a slew of upbeat economic data, especially on the job, auto and housing fronts are providing strong support to the sector.
Currently, RTH has a Zacks ETF Rank of 1 or 'Strong Buy' rating with a Medium risk outlook, suggesting continued outperformance in the months ahead.
Further, many of the segments that make up this ETF have a strong Zacks Industry Rank, so there is definitely some promise for those who want to ride this surging ETF a little further.
